var childContent= new dijit.layout.ContentPane({
                       content:data
        });
    childContent.placeAt(commentPane.containerNode,'last');
};
. Ah, ok. I'm such an ignoramus with this stuff...
But I think maybe a better way is to just have the browser do a pub
and send back the message from node back over the Sockjs connection.
That seems simpler!
On Thu, Jan 5, 2012 at 10:10 AM, Michael Bridgen
reply@reply.github.com
wrote:

@fostercraig: To be honest I am not completely sure of the reconnect semantics of SockJS. Just opening another ought to work however.
One possible hitch is that SockJS (and Socket.IO, and HTTP for that matter) is limited to two HTTP open connections to any given host; in practice this means that in general one can only maintain one SockJS connection to a host, since the fallback needs one connection for sending and one for long polling.

